---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Breadcrumbs from '../../components/Breadcrumbs.astro';
import CTABlock from '../../components/CTABlock.astro';
import { business, BASE } from '../../data/business';
import { postBySlug, postsBySlugs, RELATED_POSTS } from '../../data/posts';
import RelatedPosts from '../../components/RelatedPosts.astro';

const post = postBySlug('storm-eowyn-fence-repairs-ayrshire')!;
const relatedPosts = postsBySlugs(RELATED_POSTS[post.slug] ?? []).slice(0, 3);
const siteUrl = business.siteUrl.replace(/\/$/, '');
const url = `${siteUrl}/blog/${post.slug}/`;
const ogImage = `${siteUrl}${post.ogImage}`;

const articleSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  '@id': `${url}#article`,
  headline: post.title,
  description: post.description,
  inLanguage: 'en-GB',
  datePublished: post.date,
  dateModified: post.date,
  author: {
    '@type': 'Person',
    name: post.author,
    worksFor: { '@id': `${siteUrl}/#business` },
  },
  publisher: { '@id': `${siteUrl}/#business` },
  image: [ogImage],
  mainEntityOfPage: url,
  articleSection: 'Storm damage & fencing',
  keywords: [post.keyword, 'storm Éowyn Ayrshire', 'fence replacement Cumnock', 'emergency fencing Kilmarnock', 'storm damage insurance fence'],
  wordCount: post.wordCount,
  about: [
    { '@type': 'Place', name: 'East Ayrshire, Scotland' },
    { '@type': 'Event', name: 'Storm Éowyn' },
  ],
};
---
<BaseLayout
  title={`${post.title} | Sorn Handyman Services`}
  description={post.description}
  canonicalPath={`/blog/${post.slug}/`}
  ogImage={ogImage}
  extraSchema={articleSchema}
>
  <Breadcrumbs trail={[
    { name: 'Home', href: `${BASE}/` },
    { name: 'Blog', href: `${BASE}/blog/` },
    { name: post.title },
  ]} />

  <article class="container-x py-10 lg:py-14 max-w-3xl">
    <header>
      <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-2 text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider text-amber-600">
        <span>{post.area}</span>
        <span aria-hidden class="text-navy-900/20">·</span>
        <span class="text-navy-900/60">{post.readMinutes} min read</span>
        <span aria-hidden class="text-navy-900/20">·</span>
        <time datetime={post.date} class="text-navy-900/60">{post.dateDisplay}</time>
      </div>
      <h1 class="mt-4 font-serif text-4xl md:text-5xl font-black text-navy-900 leading-tight">
        {post.title}
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-5 text-lg text-navy-900/75">
        Storm Éowyn put a red weather warning over the whole of central Scotland
        on 24 January 2025. We spent the three weeks that followed doing almost
        nothing but fencing. Here is what we saw across East Ayrshire, what
        the repair actually costs, and what your home insurance will (and will
        not) pay for.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="prose-sorn mt-8 text-lg cv-auto">
      <p>
        Friday 24 January 2025 was the strongest named storm to hit Scotland
        in a decade. Gusts through the central belt peaked at over 100mph and
        the Met Office red warning covered every postcode we work in — Ayrshire,
        Renfrewshire, Lanarkshire. By Saturday morning our WhatsApp was a
        wall of photos. Most of them were fences on the ground.
      </p>
      <p>
        We wrote down what we saw that weekend and in the three weeks that
        followed because it was the busiest fencing stretch we have ever had.
        If you are still staring at a flat line of panels and thinking "is it
        worth fixing or should I replace the lot?", this is the honest version
        of what we tell people on the phone.
      </p>

      <h2>What Storm Éowyn did to East Ayrshire fences</h2>
      <p>
        The damage pattern was consistent from Mauchline down to
        <a href={`${BASE}/areas/cumnock/`}>Cumnock</a> and east towards
        Muirkirk. Closeboard and feather-edge panels on exposed back gardens
        were the first to go. Concrete posts mostly held. Timber 75×75 posts
        snapped clean at ground level — that is where rot usually sits, hidden
        inside the post-mix collar. The wind found the weak ones and the weak
        ones gave.
      </p>
      <p>
        The three patterns we logged most often:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Full lines down.</strong> Three or more consecutive panels
          flat, usually with one or two snapped posts. Typical on gardens
          facing south-west across an open field.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Single-panel failures.</strong> One panel blown through
          or out of its channel, posts intact. Very common on closeboard where
          the panel was 10+ years old and the feather-edge boards had
          cupped.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Gate and gravel-board damage.</strong> Gates torn off hinges,
          gravel boards split. A lot of this in
          <a href={`${BASE}/areas/kilmarnock/`}>Kilmarnock</a> back courts
          where gates had been sistered one too many times already.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Make-safe now vs full replace later</h2>
      <p>
        Not every fence needs replacing the week after a storm. If your line
        is down but the posts are sound, a <strong>make-safe</strong> is the
        right first call — we re-fix whatever panels we can rescue, prop
        anything that is leaning, and book the permanent repair in for a
        dry week when the ground is workable. That keeps the dog in and the
        garden private while you wait on insurance or a quieter weekend.
      </p>
      <p>
        Honest make-safe and <a href={`${BASE}/services/fence-repair/`}>fence
        repair</a> price bands for standard domestic gardens in the KA
        postcodes:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Re-fix one panel, sister a leaning post — £45 to £90.</li>
        <li>Replace one snapped post and re-hang panels — £120 to £180.</li>
        <li>Gate re-hang with new hinges and drop-bolt — £70 to £120.</li>
        <li>
          Temporary prop-and-strap for a whole line so it holds until the
          permanent fit — £60 to £140 depending on length.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Full <a href={`${BASE}/services/fencing/`}>fence replacement</a>
        with new posts in fast-set and new 6ft closeboard panels runs around
        £55 per panel including the post and gravel board, assuming we can
        reuse the existing line. A 10-panel back garden with a new gate
        typically lands between £650 and £900 all-in. We set posts in
        Postfix, use 100×100 pressure-treated, concrete gravel boards where
        the ground is damp, and do not skimp on arris rails.
      </p>

      <h2>What home insurance usually covers — and what it does not</h2>
      <p>
        Most UK buildings-insurance policies <em>do</em> cover storm damage to
        fencing, but there are three lines of small print that catch people
        out almost every time. We are not insurance advisors — ring your own
        insurer before you start — but here is the pattern we see every week
        on customer claims.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>What usually gets paid:</strong>
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Direct wind damage to the fence on a named-storm day.</li>
        <li>Damage to gates, gate posts and gate hinges.</li>
        <li>
          Replacement on a like-for-like basis (so closeboard stays
          closeboard, not an upgrade to composite).
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        <strong>What usually does not get paid:</strong>
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          Fences that were already rotten — insurers call this
          "gradual deterioration" and it is the most common decline reason.
        </li>
        <li>
          Gardens where the damage is cosmetic (cupped boards, loose caps)
          but the fence is still standing.
        </li>
        <li>
          Upgrades — if you want to go from timber to composite, you pay the
          difference.
        </li>
        <li>
          The excess — usually £100 to £350 — which often exceeds the cost
          of a single-panel repair anyway.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Practical advice: <strong>photograph everything</strong> before you
        touch it. Wide shot of the whole line, close-up of each snapped post
        showing the break, and a shot of the panel in situ on the ground.
        Insurers want evidence the damage happened on the storm date, not
        three weeks earlier. We send itemised invoices with date, address,
        a plain-English scope of works and a split between labour and
        materials — that is what the claims team wants to see.
      </p>

      <h2>How fast can you get us out?</h2>
      <p>
        In the middle of a named-storm aftermath, our diary usually stretches
        to two to three weeks for a full replacement across
        <a href={`${BASE}/areas/`}>the East Ayrshire patch</a>. Make-safe
        visits — where we prop the line, re-fix what we can and get your
        garden dog-proof — we normally do inside 48 hours even in storm
        week, because we keep a separate "emergency" slot running.
      </p>
      <p>
        The fastest way to get on the list is to WhatsApp
        <a href={`https://wa.me/${business.whatsapp.replace('+','')}`}>a few
        photos</a> to Aidan with the postcode and how long the fence line
        is. We send a ballpark back the same day and a firm quote by email
        once we have walked it.
      </p>

      <h2>FAQ</h2>
      <h3>Was Storm Éowyn an insurance-recognised named storm?</h3>
      <p>
        Yes — it was named by the Met Office and carried a red warning across
        central Scotland on 24 January 2025, which is what UK insurers
        typically look for when assessing storm cover.
      </p>
      <h3>My neighbour's fence fell into my garden. Whose insurance pays?</h3>
      <p>
        The fence owner's policy, normally. Check the deeds or title plan for
        the T-mark — the side of the boundary the fence belongs to. We can
        repair either side regardless of who is paying.
      </p>
      <h3>Do you do emergency fencing outside daylight hours?</h3>
      <p>
        For a make-safe where the damage is a hazard — yes, any hour. There
        is a £60 out-of-hours minimum between 10pm and 6am. For full
        replacements we book in daylight when we can see what we are doing.
      </p>
      <h3>Will you fit composite or metal fencing?</h3>
      <p>
        We fit timber closeboard, feather-edge, overlap and hit-and-miss as
        standard. Composite fence panels and steel railings we will quote on
        request — they take longer to source.
      </p>

      <div class="not-prose mt-10 rounded-2xl border border-navy-900/10 bg-navy-50/50 p-6">
        <p class="text-sm text-navy-900/60">Written by</p>
        <p class="mt-1 font-serif text-xl font-bold text-navy-900">{post.author}</p>
        <p class="mt-2 text-navy-900/75 text-sm">{post.authorBio}</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <RelatedPosts posts={relatedPosts} eyebrow="Keep reading" heading="Related posts" variant="tinted" />

  <CTABlock
    heading="Fence down after a storm? We'll get you back on the list."
    sub="WhatsApp Aidan a wide photo and the postcode. We'll come back the same day with a make-safe slot and a ballpark for the full repair."
    location="Ayrshire"
  />
</BaseLayout>
